58th Street, north side, west from between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues, showing at right, tanks of the Amsterdam Gas Company, and in the left centre background the Interborough Rapid Transit Company power house.

May 20, 1927.

P. L. Sperr.

Tenth Ave. (left), at and adjoining the S.W. corner of West 58th (right) Street, showing a clearance at the corner where former Nos. 885 to 889 Amsterdam Ave. stood. Shown on the right is an extensive view westward on West 58th Street, to the North (Hudson) River.

December 19, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Tenth Ave., west side, north from West 58th to 59th Streets, showing occupying this block front, the Haaren High School. This structure formerly housed De Witt Clinton High School. View No. 2 depicts the southern side of same, being the West 58th Street frontage as seen across a clearance at the S.W. corner of this point.

December 19, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Tenth Ave., west side, north from West 58th to 59th Streets, showing occupying this block front, the Haaren High School. This structure formerly housed De Witt Clinton High School. View No. 2 depicts the southern side of same, being the West 58th Street frontage as seen across a clearance at the S.W. corner of this point.

December 19, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Tenth Ave., east side, north from West 58th (right) Street. When north of the next intersection this thoroughfare changes its name to become Amsterdam Ave. The low buildings on the right are units of Roosevelt Hospital which occupies that entire block between 58th and 59th Streets, east from Tenth to Ninth Avenues. Occupying the westerly portion of the next block are units of the College of Physicians and Surgeons with the Sloane Maternity Hospital (7-story structure) at the N.E. corner of 59th Street and the Vanderbilt Clinic (3-story) at the S.E. corner of 60th Street.

November 30, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
